message.text:
#Hiragana Master
Say it Together! Basic Japanese Words in Japanese Alphabetical Order.
Today's Word is "MU" MUKASHI BANASHI　#nihongo
日本の単語を五十音順にわかりやすく紹介！「む」かしばなし（昔話、Old Tale）


As elsewhere in the world, Japan has lots of old tales which have been transmitted by word of mouth for generations, and every Japanese kid grows up listen to. 

Reading a Mukashi Banashi is a good way to learn Japanese old customs and cultures, and even unique expressions. 
For example, many of Mukashi Banashi start with "Mukashi mukashi, arutokoroni...(むかしむかし、あるところに..., Once upon a time, there was ...in a certain place)", as one of my favorite story "Hanasaka Jiisan (花咲かじいさん, Old Man Who Makes Flowers Bloom)" does!

Please check out Japanese Mukashi Banashi at the link below, or at the Japan Foundation's libraries, and get a hint of Japanese old customs and expressions!
https://www.jpf.go.jp/j/japanese/survey/tsushin/bn/6-014.html

みなさんの国にはどんな昔話がありますか？
日本にもたくさんの昔話があり、小さいときから色んなお話を聞いて育ちます。
「むかしむかし、あるところに・・・」はお決まりの言葉。日本の昔話を読んで、日本独特の言葉や文化を学んでみませんか？

message.text:
#Hiragana Master
Say it Together! Basic Japanese Words in Japanese Alphabetical Order.
Today's Word is "MI" MIKAN　#nihongo 
日本の単語を五十音順にわかりやすく紹介！「み」かん（蜜柑、Japanese Mandarin Orange）
http://words.marugotoweb.jp/search_detail.php?id=2034%2C924&p=1&q=みかん&source=search&lang=en


In Japan, "Mikan" is traditionally associated with winter because it is filled with necessary vitamins for the winter season. Since it has a soft skin, we often enjoy Mikan Skin Art with family or friends while sitting warm under the "kotatsu", another symbol of winter, a table over an electric heater.

Why don't you try Mikan Skin Art and tell us how it goes!?

日本ではみかんは冬の果物！こたつでぬくぬく温まりながら、家族や友だちとみかんの皮むきアートを楽しんだりしますよ。
みなさんもやってみませんか～？
＃みかんの皮アート　＃MikanSkinArt

message.text:
Coming-of-Age Day
When have you become an "adult"? 
In Japan, the official age of majority is 20 years old. 
Today, the second Monday of January is a national holiday dedicated to congratulate all those who have reached this age. Every local and prefectural offices invite young adults for a ceremony, often followed by an alumni association, to salute their passage into adulthood. 
Most women dress up in furisode(ふりそで、振り袖), a formal style of kimono with long sleeves worn only by unmarried women. Many men, too, wear montsuki hakama (もんつきはかま、紋付袴), a formal traditional kimono with family crests. 
The bright colored kimonos and fancy atmosphere cheer up every town, reminding us of this important custom in encouraging citizenship and responsibility among the community.
If you were to wear a kimono on a once-in-a-lifetime occasion like this, what color would you choose and why?  
成人の日
あなたが「大人」になったのはいつですか？
日本の成人年齢は20歳です。
本日1月の第2月曜日は成人の日。20歳を迎えた成人は各市町村での式典で祝福を受け、そのまま同窓会になだれ込みます。
多くの女性は振袖で、男性は紋付袴やスーツでおめかしします。
今日はどの街も色とりどりの着物と華やかな雰囲気で賑わいました。地域の一住人としての責任を自覚する大切な行事です。
一生に一度の晴れ姿、あなたなら何色の着物を選びますか？
